Time Series Sales Forecasting – Project Summary Report
1. Business Objective
The objective of this project was to forecast future daily sales using historical sales data. Accurate forecasts help optimize inventory planning, staffing, promotions, and business decision-making while reducing stock-outs and overstock situations.
2. Data Analysis & Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)
Performed comprehensive exploratory analysis to understand the data before modeling.
Data Validation
Checked dataset dimensions and summary statistics.
Identified and handled missing values.
Removed duplicate records.
Converted Date from string to datetime format.
Sorted data chronologically.
Set Date as the DataFrame index for time-series operations.
Exploratory Analysis
Performed group-by analysis on:
Store
Holiday
Promotion
Visualized overall sales trend.
Plotted rolling mean to identify long-term trends and smooth fluctuations.
Applied STL (Seasonal-Trend decomposition) to analyze trend, seasonality, and residual components.
Detected anomalies using the Z-score method.
3. Data Cleaning
Treated anomalies identified through Z-score analysis.
Ensured a clean and consistent dataset for forecasting.
Verified data integrity after preprocessing.
4. Feature Engineering
Stationarity Check
Performed the Augmented Dickey-Fuller (ADF) Test.
The p-value indicated that the series was already stationary, so differencing was not required.
Model Parameter Identification
Generated ACF and PACF plots on the stationary series.
Observed no significant seasonal pattern.
Selected appropriate ARIMA (p, d, q) parameters based on ACF and PACF analysis.
Time-Series Features
Created predictive features including:
Lag features
Rolling mean features
Rolling statistics
Date-based features (day, month, day of week, etc.)
5. Model Development
Classical Time Series Model
Built an ARIMA model using the selected (p, d, q) values obtained from ACF/PACF analysis.
Machine Learning Model
Built an XGBoost Regressor using lag, rolling, and time-based features.
Compared the machine learning approach with the classical time-series model.
6. Model Evaluation
Used a time-based train-test split to preserve temporal order and prevent data leakage.
Evaluation metrics:
MAE: 95
MAPE: 20%
The XGBoost model effectively captured temporal patterns using engineered features and produced satisfactory forecasting performance.
7. Conclusion
Completed end-to-end time-series forecasting from preprocessing to model evaluation.
Used statistical techniques (ADF, ACF, PACF, STL) to understand the data characteristics.
Applied feature engineering to improve predictive performance.
Trained both a classical forecasting model (ARIMA) and a machine learning model (XGBoost).
Evaluated performance using MAE and MAPE, demonstrating a robust forecasting pipeline suitable for business forecasting applications.